    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but it still feels a bit weird. i saw someone call it \"spooky action at a distance\" once. why did they call it spooky? is there something inherently \"unexplained\" about how the information seems to travel so fast?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Spooky action at a distance,\" as Einstein famously called it, perfectly captures the unsettling nature of entanglement. It's spooky because it seems to violate our everyday understanding of locality—the idea that an object can only be directly influenced by its immediate surroundings. The instantaneous correlation between entangled particles suggests a connection that transcends the speed limit of light. However, it's important to note that while the correlation is instant, this connection *cannot* be used to send actual information faster than light.",
      "source": "target",
